Verres wished to get the statues into his possession, but not by pur- chase. Cicero adds that he found he could not do it either by force, by stealth, or by entreaty in the way of ‘ precario? The passage seems to be an allusion to the three ‘ vitia possessionis,' or wrongful modes of obtaining possession, as in Pro Caecina, c. 32, ‘ut nec vi nec clam nec precario pos- sederit ,·' and Terence, Eunuch. ii. 3. 27, ‘ hanc tu mihi vel vi vel clam vel precario fac tradas?
